  "readingTitle": "Stress and the written accent (á é í ó ú)",
  "reading": "<p>Two simple rules tell you which syllable is stressed:</p>\n            <ul>\n              <li>Words ending in a <strong>vowel, n or s</strong> → stress the <strong>second-to-last</strong> syllable: <span data-say=\"hablo\">hablo</span>, <span data-say=\"joven\">joven</span>.</li>\n              <li>Words ending in any <strong>other consonant</strong> → stress the <strong>last</strong> syllable: <span data-say=\"hablar\">hablar</span>, <span data-say=\"ciudad\">ciudad</span>.</li>\n              <li>A <strong>written accent</strong> overrides both and shows the stress: <span data-say=\"región\">región</span>, <span data-say=\"sonreír\">sonreír</span>.</li>\n            </ul>\n            <p>Accents can change meaning: <span data-say=\"sí\">sí</span> (yes) vs <em>si</em> (if); <span data-say=\"él\">él</span> (he) vs <em>el</em> (the). The upside-down <strong>¿ ¡</strong> open questions and exclamations.</p>",
